09. Escape Room
# User Input
Have you noticed that all of the Java programs we've written so far are only based on what you write to the program? Our java programs get much more interesting when the users get to change it!

In Java, we can use the scanner to collect user information and create more dynamic programs that can change. 🌪️

import java.util.Scanner;

public class Greetings {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter your name: ");
        String name = scanner.nextLine();

        System.out.println(name);
    }
}

## How it works
This import statement tells Java we want to use the scanner.

import java.util.Scanner;

The scanner object: Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in); sets up the scanner to read input from the user.

In our program example, we used the scanner.nextLine() method to read strings, but we can also use

scanner.nextDouble()
scanner.nextBoolean()
scanner.nextInt()
to read and save double, boolean, and int data types to a variable.

Don't worry about what an object or method means just yet! We'll come back to it. For now, just know we'll need it in our program.

Instructions
We have the following escape room clue we need to solve!

I speak without a mouth and hear without ears. I have no body, but I come alive with the wind. What am I?

Use the scanner to create a program that asks the user for their answer to the riddle. At the end, be sure to test it, and end the program with a congratulations phrase!
 import java.util.Scanner;

public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Write your code here 💖
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("I speak without a mouth and hear without ears. I have no body, but I come alive with the wind. What am I?");
        String answer = sc.nextLine();
        if(answer.equals("echo")){
            System.out.println("Congratulations! You solved the riddle!");
        } else{
            System.out.println("Not the right answer!!!..... TRY AGAIN");
        }
        sc.close();
    }
}
